It's an app on App Store. Annual subscription is $120, but for first time users it's $20. So I got it for $20. In the app, you can select your preferred pharmacy (I chose Bartells in Sammamish). Each visit with a doctor costs $1. Visit is a chat session with a doctor, who asks about symptoms and current medications etc. The whole process took a total of 10 minutes (excluding ~20 minutes of doctor's availability after requesting a visit). The doctor, then told that he has sent the prescription to the pharmacy. Anu Gopalam & a few other people suggested to use [https://www.goodrx.com/](https://www.goodrx.com/) to get discounts on medicine. I put the name of medicine on the website and it showed the cheapest price for the medicine at various pharmacies. I chose Bartells and got a coupon. After a couple of hours I called the pharmacy and confirmed that they had the prescription. I provided them the coupon details over the phone, which reduced the price of medicine from ~$65 to ~$9. Afterwards, I went to the pharmacy and collected the medicine. So, overall I paid ~$30 for getting the prescription and medicines. The whole process took 3-4 hours and was super smooth. Thorpe (1887-1953) was Sac & Fox and attended Haskell Institute and Carlisle. He won Gold Medals for the Pentathlon and Decathlon at the 1912 Olympics in Stockholm. He is considered \"The Greatest Athlete of the Twentieth Century.\" Today, there’s a fitness center on the Haskell campus that bears his name. in usa","profileImage":"https://scontent-sea1-1.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t31.18172-8/cp0/c18.0.50.50a/p50x50/13668868_618035225044997_3415512146372037201_o.jpg?_nc_cat=104&ccb=1-5&_nc_sid=ac9ee4&_nc_ohc=5pO3oc55F2wAX8BgxC0&_nc_ht=scontent-sea1-1.xx&oh=00_AT82izvQ_JmMu6aOwUhPZx3TR2NCVG2hblnFvm_hW6TgRQ&oe=61FF38A2","subscriberCount":29998,"url":"https://www.facebook.com/groups/3497142250","platform":"Facebook","platformId":"3497142250","accountType":"facebook_group","pageCategory":"none","verified":false},"languageCode":"und","legacyId":0,"id":"9050762|10156878375612251"},{"platformId":"503055433070371_3779702032072345","platform":"Facebook","date":"2020-04-21 00:15:40","updated":"2022-01-06 20:55:43","type":"photo","description":"April 20, 1945 is deemed a memorable day for the Mississippi Choctaw. It is the day when the people voted to reclaim our destiny. As we celebrate the 75th anniversary of the recognition of the Mississippi Band of Choctaw Indians as a sovereign Tribal government, we think about the perseverance of hardships endured by our people to get us to where we are today.\n\nPrior to federal recognition, the Choctaw people had no say about their lives. A century earlier, our ancestors, the once-strong Choctaw Nation of Mississippi, had been robbed of their lands through a series of treaties that greatly benefited the newly-formed United States of America.  These treaties gave little to no care to well-being of the Choctaw needs. The final treaty in 1830, the Treaty of Dancing Rabbit Creek, effectively abolished the Tribe and forcibly removed the majority of the Choctaw to Indian Territory.\n\nBut things didn’t change overnight after 1945. It took several years for the Tribe to shake itself loose from the grip of the federal government. In the late 1970s, the Tribe established the manufacturing industry. On the reservation in the 1980s, the Tribe took over control of law enforcement and education from the BIA. In 1994, the Choctaw Health Center finally became fully operated by the Tribe. In that same year, the Tribe opened the Silver Star Hotel and Casino, which propelled the Tribe to economic success and, along with its fellow properties, now known collectively as Pearl River Resort, is one of Mississippi’s largest private employers. \n\nChoctaw Self-Determination is the doctrine behind the Tribe’s success, which is the idea that individual Tribal members and the Tribal government should take responsibility and be self-sufficient. As we look to the future and keep moving forward, let’s take a moment and recognize those leaders who have paved the way for our current success.\n\nAfter the 1934 Indian Re-organization Act the Choctaw Agency created the Tribal Business Committee which was a group of Choctaws that helped write the first Constitution and push for the vote in 1945. \n\nThe first Tribal Council Meeting took place in July 10, 1945 which elected a temporary Chairman, Will Jimmie, to call the meeting to order and open nominations for Chairman and Vice-Chairman. Joe Chitto was nominated as the first Chairman at this first Tribal Council meeting and served until 1949. Emmett York served from 1949-1953; Joe Chitto served once again from 1953-1955; Emmett York once again served as Chairman from 1955-1959; from 1959-1965 Phillip Martin served as Chairman; in 1966 Robert Benn served as Chairman before becoming the first Choctaw Superintendent of the Choctaw Agency; Clay Gibson served from 1966-1967; Emmett York served from 1967-1971 and the last to serve in with a Chairman title was Phillip Martin from 1971-1975. \n\nIn 1975 the Constitution was changed to allow for the democratic election of a Tribal Chief. The first modern day Tribal Chief of the Mississippi Band of Choctaw Indians was the late Chief Calvin J. Isaac who served from 1975-1979. From 1979-2007 the late Chief Phillip Martin served and is the longest serving Chief of the Tribe. Miko Beasley Denson served from 2007-2011. Chief Phyliss J. Anderson became the first female Tribal Chief and served from 2011-2019. In July 2019 Cyrus Ben was sworn-in as the fifth and youngest democratically elected Tribal Chief of the Mississippi Band of Choctaw Indians. \n\nYakoki, thank you! To all Tribal members, let us never forget our past…our struggles, our challenges, and our fight for survival. These obstacles throughout history help us appreciate the success we’ve obtained after our formal recognition in 1945. \n\nIronically, we celebrate our anniversary in the middle of a dark time that will forever be embedded in our nations’ history. Just as our ancestors fought and persevered against hatred, racism, prejudice, ignorance and extinction, we can be united in the fight against the coronavirus outbreak. Let us focus on helping each other, caring for each other and doing our part to protect each other. \nMay our future be filled with wonderful opportunities and an even more improved quality of life for our people. Today, with a Tribal enrollment of 11,107, we recognize our existence, 75 years of strength, determination and perseverance! For 75 years, we remain the Mississippi Band of Choctaw Indians. \n\nOur Ancestors Fought to Stay and Survive.\nOur Elders Fought to Be Recognized.\nWe Fight to Never Be Forgotten.\n\nChahta Hapia Instead of breaking new ground to knock down barriers, American Indian Heritage Day in Texas (AIHD) will no longer participate in the development of a vital ethnic learning curriculum. AIHD co-sponsored this initiative to give the American Indian community an opportunity to address the stereotyped American Indian. History is limited to single pages and edited shuttered visions of our Ancestors were dismantled in the storyboard of our double identity and ruptured our existence. Imagine the historical trauma of “yesterday’s end of an era” from our phases of genocide. We have separated our organization from this project totally, leaving and unfolding a much needed space which erased what could have been a comfortable setting for students to welcome a cross-cultural learning exposure of American Indian’s preservation. This history is deeply engrained into the historical dialogue of 573 federally recognized tribes from the State of Texas to the United States nationwide that could have been life changing. We chose to leave the curriculum planning stage where our passion was not heard and overlooked our strategy, executive core committee and implementation to bring truth to American Indian’s fictional blurred lines of this land’s original people. We saw a pattern where too many outside voices overpowered the American Indian stage by adding too many layers of international voices that were overlooked in other ethnic studies books in the Texas Education Agency. This cultural misappropriation was a key element that made us feel as a disadvantaged minority. When we have a new generation of American Indians who feel they can dishonor our elders and speak over them with their perceived wisdom without repercussions, this disrespect was not a difficult decision. Our responsibility is to promote the right curriculum to reach that one American Indian student to instill pride in their tribal Confirmed Schedule below, to help you plan accordingly. **Beginner Session (1 hour session*):** 26-Apr Sunday 430pm to 530pm **might extend by 15 min. * **Adv. Session - (~Five 1 hour sessions): ** 27-Apr to 1-May 430pm to 530pm Stay Safe, Stay Healthy ! ************ Dear all, As the corona virus & lockdown brought a lot of challenges to the external world, it also gives us an rare opportunity & time to explore our inner world. In these tough times, it’s extremely important to protect and enhance our mental and spiritual health consciously. Personally, for last 6 years I have been practicing advanced Hatha Yoga, Siddha Yoga (Vaasi), advanced pranayama (breathing techniques) and meditation practices. My family had taken full advantage of this lock-down period to regularly practice yoga together. I would like to offer my knowledge and experience to all who want to benefit from these potent practices and stay healthy. Continuous practice of these techniques will help you to deal with anything the world throws at you with grace & ease. If you are relatively new to Yoga wanting to explore or an avid practitioner who’s looking for ways to accelerate your spiritual journey – all are most welcome. **This is absolutely free for all**. My only request is that you practice what you learn and benefit from it. **Tentative Date: **27-Apr to 1-May. For Beginners: * Training Session: 1hr via video-call. This will cover 20-30 min of daily practice. * Covers: Beginner Yoga asanas, Pranayama techniques. * Practice correction sessions, as required. * You are expected to practice daily at your own time. For those who want to push the envelope: * Training sessions: 1hr/day for 4-5 days. This will cover 50-60 min of daily practice * Advanced HathaYoga, Pranayama techniques, advanced meditation * Regular Practice correction sessions, as required * You are expected to practice daily at your own time If you are interested, please let me know via FB message or email: ***subtlerdimensions@gmail.com*** Also, please mention if you are a beginner or avid practitioner. I’ll share the session & further details via email. He helped countless people, an honest person and a mediator, always ready to provide support to anyone, an amazing human being all around. \n\nA person who loved to make everyone laugh. \nApeople’s person,, man of moral values, He lit up the room . If he was in the room, people were drawn to him.\n\nHe was simply an honest man, an amazing personality came to USA in 80’s, and left no one behind to say anything against him.  He was a great mentor with his great experience of life and wisdom. He was true problem solver and best companion. \n\nHe loved being surrounded by the ones and with biggest list of friendship from houston to all over USA and from Lahore to Pakistan, he adored the most in gatherings and being part of serval NGO’s & Organizations as Member, Co Founder, President & Volunteer with vision to help & assist  the community for decades starring from Pakistan to USA.   He was a part of several charity organizations. \n\nThis is remindar to all of us, One day, we all have to leave this world alone ! \n​\nhe was tested positive for the Covid-19.  We all were praying for his fastest recovery but it was not what been written for him.  \n\nDespite by family warnings to stay at home but He chosen himself to help his employees and neighborhood and to keep the supply running for those poor people in his neighborhood store who cannot afford and most of them were also getting groceries for free due to current crisis and were loyal customers for decades and this was the time to giveback to them if they couldn’t afford. \n\nwith several precautions and instructions to follow , who knew that just to take one delivery from a delivery driver who had positive with Covid-19 and signing an invoice will take him away to the place where no one comes back.  \n\n'Surely we belong to Allah and to Him shall we return,  \n\nYou will be truly remember in our hearts ! Indian Students Association!⁣ @utdisa⁣ ⁣ UTD is home to hundreds of Indian students. ISA represents each and every one of them and apart from striving to make everyone feel at home miles away from home, we also draw a flux of colorful Indian culture through our various programs. The purpose of the ISA is to provide an opportunity for all students of Indian origin to interact and share the joy of the culture and heritage of India, and to educate other students, by bringing awareness. We achieve this goal by involving every Indian student on campus through cultural events, workshops, and by celebration of Indian festivals. We also serve as the first touch point of every Indian student coming to UTD.⁣ ⁣ ISA’s benefitted the UTD community through the following: “The number one project that we did this year, and have been doing for the last 25 years, is Pickups and accommodation. We picked up roughly 1000 students from the airport and provided them temporary accommodation to them till they settled in to their new apartments. This makes sure that the students feel at home from the time they land in Dallas. With countless sleepless nights and hours of efforts from our volunteers, our pick up and accommodation success rate was yet again 100% this year - No student was missed!⁣ ⁣ In addition ISA took part Thank yo...","message":"\uD83D\uDE4F PLEASE TAKE A MOMENT TO READ AND HELP\uD83D\uDE4F \uD83D\uDC9B\uD83D\uDC9BAkshaya Tritiya Special Announcement\uD83D\uDC9B\uD83D\uDC9B Hare Krishna, Akshaya Tritiya is the appearance day of Lord Parasurama and it is also the day that Mother Ganga descended to the earth. It is the beginning of Candana-yatra. Many of Lord Krishna’s other pastimes also took place on this day, specifically those which highlight Krishna’s generous and intimate reciprocation with his devotees. On this day, Sudama gave the Lord a tiny portion of chipped rice and was rewarded with untold opulence. It is on today, Pandavas received Akshayapatra, inexhaustible vessel from Sun God. Traditionally, this is the best day for starting any important endeavors. Vyasadeva chose this day to start writing the great epic Mahabharata, for example. Every year, construction of the huge Ratha Yatra carts in Jagannath Puri also starts on this day. Now, as the global pandemic of COVID-19 is upon us, we are concerned for all our congregation, well-wishers and friends. We have already offered names of our patrons and monthly donors registered thru the Automatic Monthly Donation Program to the lotus feet of Sri Sri Radha Kunjabihari, we request our patrons and monthly donors to please accept the blessings from the most merciful Sri Sri Radha Kunjabihari for wellbeing and protection of them and their families. On this auspicious day again, we will be offering puja for them and their family members' welfare and health. These are the only names we have at this time and we do not want to keep this limited, we are opening up opportunity for everyone to give their names so we can request top blessings from most merciful Sri Sri Radha Kunjabihari. Starting tomorrow special prayers, abhishek and tulasi with sandalwood pulp will be offered on behalf of all the people who provide us their names to the lotus feet of Their Lordships Sri Sri Radha Kunjabihari. You may also appreciate that the temple facility is operational which means heat and power usage is unchanged, temple services are going as normal which means offering morning abhishek to the deities, morning and night dressing, bhoga (food) and aarati being offered six times a day to the deities is all going on by a limited dedicated team of pujaris. To support all this we exclusively rely on any monthly donations and the donations we receive thru the month - but since temple has been closed to public, we have less donations but same expenses. We encourage and humbly request support from all of you, and one way is to signup for the Automatic Monthly Donation Program (AMDP). We will accumulate names of people who signup thru coming weeks of COVID-19 crisis and offer names to Sri Sri Radha Kunjabihari every Sunday for their and their family's health and welfare. It breaks my heart to learn that unemployment in the US alone amounts to more than 26 million which is 15% of the US workforce. We have to fall apart to create a new and meaningful life – a life that makes us even more strong and robust. The truth is we may look back at our life and someday talk about the strength and wisdom we achieved living in the time of the pandemic called COVID-19. We will have to wait and see how many different types of businesses boom at this time. There have been too many articles on how the COVID-19 has seen many blessings in nature. But since my focus is on people and organizations, I will stick to my forte.\n\n1. If you are a small business owner and have delayed taking your business online in the past, now is the best time to do so. If your business is not online, you do not exist in the market at this point. Social networking and connecting should be a priority even if you do not appreciate it.\n\n2. This particular weakness may set you back years in your business in terms of success. Identify how you feel about change and ask yourself if this is a valid claim.\n\n3. Your business must be evolving and if you practice the same customs for years without change, your business will suffer. If your natural market does not require your products, you cannot keep selling it, no matter how good your customer service or product is. The best example of this is Blockbuster.\n\n4. Business owners are good at identifying their opportunities and threats but when making decisions on how to grow and implement ideas, it is important to list as many ways as possible and consider the wild factors. There is a human tendency of hesitation or avoiding actions that have not been taken before in an organization. Business owners and top management prefer to stick to ideas generated that are close to the organizational culture. This is true when it comes to private practices as well such as lawyers' or physicians' offices.\n\n5. Be aware of your company culture. Be innovative and instigate change even if you think it is very different from your previous habits.
